  "prompt": "Can you make Bisquick pancakes without eggs?",
  "response": "Yes, you absolutely can make Bisquick pancakes without eggs! Here's a recipe and some tips:\n\n**Basic Bisquick Pancake Recipe (Egg-Free):**\n\n*   1 1/2 cups Bisquick baking mix\n*   1 cup milk (dairy or non-dairy works)\n*   1 tablespoon oil (vegetable, canola, or melted coconut oil)\n*   1 tablespoon sugar (optional, for a touch more sweetness)\n\n**Instructions:**\n\n1.  **Combine Ingredients:** In a bowl, whisk together the Bisquick, milk, oil, and sugar (if using) until just combined.  Don't overmix! A few lumps are okay.\n2.  **Heat Griddle/Pan:** Heat a lightly oiled griddle or frying pan over medium heat. You can use butter, oil, or cooking spray. A good way to test if it's hot enough is to sprinkle a few drops of water on the surface. If the water sizzles and evaporates quickly, it's ready.\n3.  **Pour Batter:** Pour 1/4 cup of batter onto the hot griddle for each pancake.\n4.  **Cook Pancakes:** Cook for 2-3 minutes per side, or until bubbles form on the surface and the edges look set. Flip and cook for another 1-2 minutes, or until golden brown.\n5.  **Serve:** Serve immediately with your favorite toppings, such as syrup, fruit, whipped cream, etc.\n\n**Tips for Success:**\n\n*   **Don't Overmix:** Overmixing develops the gluten in the Bisquick, which can result in tough pancakes. Mix until just combined.\n*   **Let the Batter Rest (Optional):** Letting the batter rest for 5-10 minutes before cooking can help the Bisquick absorb the liquid and result in slightly fluffier pancakes.\n*   **Adjust Liquid:** If your batter seems too thick, add a tablespoon or two more milk until you reach your desired consistency. If it's too thin, add a tablespoon of Bisquick.\n*   **Heat Control:** Keep the heat at medium. Too high, and the pancakes will burn on the outside before they're cooked through. Too low, and they'll be pale and flat.\n*   **Non-Dairy Milk:** Almond milk, soy milk, oat milk, or any other non-dairy milk alternative works well in this recipe.\n*   **Flavor Variations:**  Add a pinch of cinnamon, vanilla extract, chocolate chips, blueberries, or mashed banana to the batter for extra flavor.\n\n**Why this works without eggs:**\n\nBisquick already contains baking powder, which is the leavening agent.  The milk and oil provide moisture and fat. Eggs would normally add richness, structure, and some leavening, but they aren't essential for making a decent pancake with Bisquick.  The texture will be slightly different (often a bit denser), but the pancakes will still be enjoyable.\n",
